WHAT IS THIS KINGDOM
The domain that defines the complete electro-optical chain from
the lens mount to the digital RAW output. It encompasses sensor
physics and metrology, the architecture of the Image Signal
Processor (ISP), lens hardware characteristics that influence the
captured image, and the stabilization systems that control
camera motion. It is the engineering layer that converts the
optical image into a calibrated, linearizable digital file.

WHY IT EXISTS
A perfect color pipeline is useless if the underlying sensor
response is uncalibrated or the ISP applies non-reversible
processing. This kingdom provides the metrological foundation
to characterize any sensor, the standard ISP stages that must
be accounted for in linearization, and the lens-hardware
interactions (vignetting, distortion, breathing) that must be
inverted or compensated. It guarantees that GIOP can ingest
the rawest possible data stream with full knowledge of its
physical origins.

HOW IT IS STRUCTURED
Five sub-domains: Sensor Metrology, ISP Pipeline Architecture,
Lens Hardware and Optical Compensation, Camera Stabilization
and Motion Models, and Sensor-Lens Interaction Models. Each
section defines the measurement protocols, mathematical models,
and design constraints, with references to ISO and EMVA
standards.

WHERE IT IS APPLIED
RAW development, camera firmware design, on-set DIT quality
control (false color, exposure evaluation), lens metadata
utilization in VFX (distortion maps), gimbal and OIS
performance characterization, and computational photography
algorithms that fuse multiple frames.

WHO USES IT
Camera engineers, RAW decoder developers, DITs, lens technicians,
pipeline TDs who ingest and linearize camera data.

WHAT PROBLEM IT SOLVES
Removes ambiguity about how a specific sensor converts photons
to code values. Defines the exact processing chain that must
be inverted to reach linear scene light. Provides the lens
correction models (distortion, fall-off) needed to align
multi-camera arrays. Guarantees that stabilization-induced
motion blur can be separated from scene motion, enabling
accurate VFX tracking.

1. SENSOR METROLOGY
All measurements follow the EMVA 1288 standard unless noted.

Quantum Efficiency (QE):
  QE(lambda) = mu_e / mu_p
Measured at each wavelength. Peak QE typically 0.6–0.9 for
front-illuminated, 0.8–0.95 for back-illuminated CMOS.

Full Well Capacity (FWC): maximum electrons per pixel.
  FWC ≈ 1000 * (pixel area in μm²) for standard CMOS.
Saturation signal S_sat = FWC * g, where g is conversion gain (DN/e-).

Conversion Gain (g): measured via Photon Transfer Curve (PTC).
  Variance_total - Variance_read = g * (Mean_Signal - Mean_Dark)
Slope of linear fit gives g in DN/e-.

Read Noise (N_read): standard deviation of signal at zero exposure.
Typical values: 1–3 e- for high-gain modes, 5–15 e- for low-gain modes.

Dynamic Range (DR):
  DR = 20 * log10(FWC / N_read)  [dB]
  DR_stops = log2(FWC / N_read)

Dark Current (D): mean thermal electron rate (e-/s) at a given
sensor temperature. Doubles approximately every 6–8 °C.

Pixel Non-Uniformity: Photo Response Non-Uniformity (PRNU) and
Dark Signal Non-Uniformity (DSNU) are corrected by flat-fielding.

Spectral Sensitivity Curves: S_sensor(lambda) = QE(lambda) *
CFA_transmittance(lambda) (including microlens and IR filter).
GIOP Bodies/ store these curves for certified cameras.

2. ISP PIPELINE ARCHITECTURE
The standard ISP transforms raw sensor data into a viewable image.
For GIOP linearization, all stages below must be invertible or
bypassed to recover scene-linear data.

Canonical stages (in processing order):
  a. Black Level Subtraction: remove the sensor's optical black
     offset (typical 64 DN for 10-bit).
  b. Defect Pixel Correction: interpolate dead/hot pixels from
     neighbors.
  c. Lens Shading Correction (LSC): compensate for vignetting
     and color shading using calibrated per-channel gain maps.
  d. White Balance: apply RGB gains to neutralize the scene
     illuminant.
  e. Demosaicing: reconstruct full RGB from the Color Filter
     Array (CFA) pattern (Bayer, X-Trans, Quad Bayer).
     GIOP endorses linear demosaicing methods (e.g., Malvar-He-
     Cutler) to avoid non-linear artifacts.
  f. Color Correction Matrix (CCM): map sensor native RGB to a
     standard color space (e.g., XYZ or sRGB) via a 3x3 matrix
     optimized for a target illuminant.
  g. Gamma Correction: apply OETF (e.g., sRGB, Rec.709) or log
     encoding (S-Log3, LogC4) for perceptual encoding.
  h. Noise Reduction (2D/3DNR) and Edge Enhancement: these are
     destructive for VFX linearization. GIOP mandates the
     availability of a "Minimal Processing" mode that bypasses
     these stages, or provides the noise model for inversion.
  i. Tone Mapping: global or local contrast adjustments. For
     GIOP compliance, this must be dissociable from the IDT.

Modern Cognitive ISP (2026 era): 20-bit internal pipeline,
real-time semantic segmentation (up to 8 layers), quad-exposure
HDR fusion, AI-driven local tone mapping and denoising. GIOP
requires that metadata describing the exact operations and
their parameters be embedded in the RAW container to permit full
inversion by external linearization tools.

3. LENS HARDWARE AND OPTICAL COMPENSATION
Lens characteristics that must be modeled and compensated:

Vignetting (natural cos^4 law):
  I_theta = I_0 * cos^4(theta)
where theta is the field angle. Mechanical vignetting
further reduces intensity off-axis, modeled by a polynomial
fit: I(x,y) = I_0 * (1 + k1*r^2 + k2*r^4 + ...), with r the
normalized radial distance.

Lens Distortion (Brown-Conrady model):
  x_dist = x * (1 + k1*r^2 + k2*r^4 + k3*r^6) + 2*p1*x*y + p2*(r^2 + 2*x^2)
  y_dist = y * (1 + k1*r^2 + k2*r^4 + k3*r^6) + p1*(r^2 + 2*y^2) + 2*p2*x*y
where (k1,k2,k3) are radial distortion coefficients and (p1,p2) are
tangential coefficients. GIOP provides inverse distortion using
STMap generation.

Chromatic Aberration: lateral (transverse) CA is modeled as a
wavelength-dependent radial shift, corrected by scaling each
channel relative to green.

Focus Breathing: the change in effective focal length with focus
distance. Quantified as the percentage change in field of view.
GIOP lens profiles include breathing compensation data for
virtual production.

4. CAMERA STABILIZATION AND MOTION MODELS
Camera motion compensation affects the effective exposure time
per pixel and introduces geometric warping.

Optical Image Stabilization (OIS): lens element shift or sensor
shift to counteract angular velocity. The compensation vector
V_comp is measured by gyroscopes. Effective blur:
  Blur_effective = |V_subject - V_comp| * t_exposure

Gimbal Stabilization (3-axis or 4DoF): feedback control system.
PID controller:
  u(t) = K_p * e(t) + K_i * integral(e dt) + K_d * de/dt
where e(t) is the angular error.

AI Horizon Lock: predictive model that anticipates user motion and
applies intelligent cropping with minimal field-of-view loss.

Rolling Shutter Compensation: in electronic stabilization, the
readout time must be accounted for. The effective transformation
is a composition of the rolling shutter skew (from sensor
readout) and the OIS shift. GIOP defines a unified 2D motion
field per frame that encapsulates all stabilization effects,
allowing VFX pipelines to remove them entirely.

5. SENSOR-LENS INTERACTION MODELS
Pixel crosstalk and microlens effects become significant at
small pixel pitches (<1 μm).

Optical crosstalk: photons passing through one color filter
may be absorbed in a neighboring pixel. Modeled by a 3x3
convolution kernel per color channel.

Microlens shading: the angular response of the pixel varies
with position on the sensor; this is compensated by LSC.

Lens-sensor alignment: flange focal distance and mount
tolerances affect field tilt and sharpness uniformity.
GIOP's lens profiles include a sensitivity matrix to these
misalignments.

